22:45.064 --> 22:51.570 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm John
Yang in Las
Vegas.

22:51.604 --> 23:02.047 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: One subject
that's sure
to come up in the final
presidential debate

23:02.081 --> 23:06.452 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is the state of the American
economy, and,
more specifically, the state of
the American

23:06.485 --> 23:08.287 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
worker.

23:08.320 --> 23:11.423 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
During the primary season, in
what now seems
ages ago, we looked at
Americans' attitudes

23:11.457 --> 23:13.225 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
toward the economy.

23:13.259 --> 23:15.828 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have an update tonight with
our partners
at Marketplace and "Frontline,"
part of our

23:15.861 --> 23:18.497 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
series on How the Deck Is
Stacked.

23:18.530 --> 23:23.369 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The unemployment rate may now
stand at 5 percent
officially, and more than 10
million new jobs

23:23.402 --> 23:25.471 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have been created during the
Obama administration.

23:25.504 --> 23:29.775 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But a new survey done by
Marketplace and Edison
Research found nearly a third of
people are

23:29.808 --> 23:34.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
afraid of losing their jobs
within the next
six months, and almost 40
percent of people

23:34.313 --> 23:37.883 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
say they are losing sleep over
their financial
situation.

23:37.916 --> 23:40.119 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Marketplace host Kai Ryssdal is
with us again.

23:40.152 --> 23:44.857 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Kai, when we first did this a
year ago, we
expected things to get better.

23:44.890 --> 23:48.460 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Why are people more anxious now
and seem less
financially secure?

23:48.494 --> 23:51.964 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KAI RYSSDAL, Marketplace: The
thing about
the economy, Hari, is that we
measure it in

23:51.997 --> 23:55.934 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
numbers, right, things like the
unemployment
rate, but people experience it
through how

23:55.968 --> 23:57.870 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
they feel.

23:57.903 --> 24:01.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what they're feeling now is
anxiety, possibly
because the election is drawing
near, possibly

24:01.440 --> 24:07.479 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
because they sense that the
headline numbers
of unemployment at 5 percent and
gross domestic

24:07.513 --> 24:11.583 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
product growing at a
percent-and-a-half, plus
or minus, they're not feeling
that in their

24:11.617 --> 24:15.321 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
lives, while, at the same time,
food prices
are going up and gas is bopping
around, $2.5,

24:15.354 --> 24:18.424 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
$3 a gallon, whatever it is.

24:18.457 --> 24:23.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
People don't feel that security
they really
would like to feel seven years
now into an

24:23.796 --> 24:25.531 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
economic expansion.

24:25.564 --> 24:28.033 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All the
numbers that you
just rattled off, what's
interesting is that

24:28.067 --> 24:31.370 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
your survey also reveals that
there's a lack
of trust in the data itself.

24:31.403 --> 24:33.339 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
KAI RYSSDAL: Oh, yes.

24:33.372 --> 24:38.210 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, this was, to me anyway, one
most of interesting
and disturbing things about this
entire survey.

24:38.243 --> 24:42.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We asked people whether they
trust government
economic data, the stuff that we
do on Marketplace

24:42.748 --> 24:47.653 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
all the time, consumer spending,
the unemployment
rate, all of that stuff; 25
percent of all

24:47.686 --> 24:51.490 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Americans completely distrust
government economic
data.

24:51.523 --> 24:56.295 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then you drill down a little
bit and you
ask them to -- who they're
voting for and

24:56.328 --> 25:02.301 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
how they feel about government
data, 48 percent
of Donald Trump voters distrust
government

25:02.334 --> 25:06.338 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
data; 5 percent of Hillary
Clinton voters
distrust the economic data.

25:06.372 --> 25:10.042 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think, if you look at
what's happening
out there on the campaign trail
and some of

25:10.075 --> 25:13.312 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the rhetoric that's coming from
the Trump
camp and from the candidate
himself, it sort

25:13.345 --> 25:16.415 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of stands to reason that his
voters are going
to distrust that data.

25:16.448 --> 25:20.452 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Speaking of
distrust, there
is also this feeling that your
survey is picking

25:20.486 --> 25:22.221 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
up on about the system being
rigged.

25:22.254 --> 25:27.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And a couple of the numbers that
leapt out
to me, 62 percent of Americans
say that the

25:27.593 --> 25:29.795 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
system, the economy is rigged.

25:29.828 --> 25:34.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then, when you break this
down, 66 percent
of Trump supporters say it's
rigged for those

25:34.733 --> 25:38.871 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who get government assistance;
62 percent
of Clinton supporters say it's
rigged for

25:38.904 --> 25:39.872 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
white Americans.

25:39.905 --> 25:41.740 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's really depends on who you
ask.

25:41.774 --> 25:45.277 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, really, regardless of who
you ask, they
still think the deck is stacked
against them.

25:45.310 --> 25:46.278 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
KAI RYSSDAL: Right.

25:46.311 --> 25:47.646 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They think the desk is stacked
against them.

25:47.679 --> 25:50.783 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And what is interesting is who
they think
the deck is stacked for.

25:50.816 --> 25:57.523 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In about 90 percent of all
responses, people
think it's stacked for
politicians, for corporations

25:57.556 --> 25:59.324 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and the rich.

25:59.358 --> 26:01.927 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what you see here is this
divide that
we're seeing now out in the
economy at large

26:01.960 --> 26:07.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
between those who have assets,
those who have
income, those who have wealth,
and those,

26:07.699 --> 26:12.371 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as we have been talking about
for a long time
now, who simply don't, and the
income inequality

26:12.404 --> 26:14.573 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
gap in this country and how it's
playing out
now in this election.

26:14.606 --> 26:17.176 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Kai, are you
surprised by
these results?

26:17.209 --> 26:19.144 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
