carrying a few
belongings and a white flag.

28:48.961 --> 28:54.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Regarding the battle, with the
help of coalition
airstrikes still smoldering
today, the Kurds

28:54.633 --> 28:57.169 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
did make important gains.

28:57.202 --> 29:02.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Under normal circumstances, the
city of Mosul
would be just 10 minutes' drive
away.

29:02.441 --> 29:08.180 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
However, for the time being, the
advance here
has been halted because advances
elsewhere

29:08.213 --> 29:10.148 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
have not gone so well.

29:10.182 --> 29:17.589 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
These Iraqi forces want to wait
for their
colleagues to catch up before
pressing ahead.

29:17.623 --> 29:22.027 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
In a house in a captured
village, we saw rooms
full of piles of earth.

29:22.060 --> 29:28.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I.S. go to great lengths to hide
their tunnels
from coalition drones.

29:28.100 --> 29:33.372 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
These networks amounted to
extensive living
quarters underground.

29:33.405 --> 29:37.676 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We saw only a faction of one
system in what
is a small village.

29:37.709 --> 29:40.712 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What must the defenses in Mosul
be like?

29:40.746 --> 29:44.950 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And for a closer
look at what
faces civilians caught in the
crossfire, I'm

29:44.983 --> 29:46.718 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
joined by David Miliband.

29:46.752 --> 29:50.555 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's the former British foreign
secretary,
now president and CEO of the
International

29:50.589 --> 29:51.823 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Rescue Committee.

29:51.857 --> 29:53.625 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Welcome to you.

29:53.659 --> 29:57.462 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I assume that a lot of people
right now face
this immediate difficult choice
of whether

29:57.496 --> 30:01.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to flee the city if they can or
remain behind
and see what happens.

30:01.366 --> 30:03.568 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID MILIBAND, Former British
Foreign Secretary:
You're absolutely right.

30:03.602 --> 30:09.074 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have our own staff now
northeast and south
of the city.

30:09.107 --> 30:13.145 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
About 1,000 people have so far
left since
the fighting began.

30:13.178 --> 30:14.880 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We have been talking to them.

30:14.913 --> 30:18.850 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the perilous choice that
they face is
between staying put and waiting
to see how

30:18.884 --> 30:24.022 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the fighting develops and, on
the other hand,
trying their find their way out
of the city,

30:24.056 --> 30:28.427 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
using all their savings for
transport, and
taking the risk with land mines,
sniper fire

30:28.460 --> 30:30.062 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and other kinds of interference.

30:30.095 --> 30:32.864 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it really is a perilous
choice and a terrifying
one.

30:32.898 --> 30:36.501 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Today, President
Obama said,
"It's not something I expect
will be easy,

30:36.535 --> 30:42.974 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but it perhaps hasn't been
publicized enough
the degree of planning, assets
and resources

30:43.008 --> 30:45.844 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
we have devoted to this
important problem."

30:45.877 --> 30:52.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, I wonder, as the fighting
begins, how
much can the interest in
refugees and humanitarians

30:52.317 --> 30:54.319 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
play into the actual fighting
strategy?

30:54.352 --> 30:55.787 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
What do you see?

30:55.821 --> 30:57.723 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID MILIBAND: I think that
there are two
things that are important.

30:57.756 --> 31:02.861 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
First of all, we have to say
loud and clear
to all those who are engaged in
the fighting

31:02.894 --> 31:07.265 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that attention to and respect
for humanitarian
needs is absolutely imperative.

31:07.299 --> 31:11.436 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Anyone with any knowledge of
Iraq, never mind
any concern about the future,
knows that the

31:11.470 --> 31:16.274 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
way in which the war is
prosecuted has a big
impact on what comes afterwards.

31:16.308 --> 31:18.477 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Secondly, there has been a lot
of planning.

31:18.510 --> 31:24.483 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The United Nations coordinator
for Iraq, Lise
Grande, is an outstanding public
servant.

31:24.516 --> 31:29.321 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The head of the United Nations
High Commission
on Refugees is in Baghdad at the
moment.

31:29.354 --> 31:31.256 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And the planning has been
serious.

31:31.289 --> 31:36.461 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the truth is, if the numbers
rise to the
kind of level that the U.N.
fears, anything

31:36.495 --> 31:42.801 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
above 500, 750, a million
people, at that
sort of scale, even at a
quarter-of-a-million

31:42.834 --> 31:46.505 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
scale, it's going to overwhelm
the camps that
are being set up.

31:46.538 --> 31:51.643 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's why we're putting
such emphasis
on the need to support those who
flee the

31:51.676 --> 31:56.648 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
city and don't find themselves
in camps, but
instead are staying with
friends, are staying

31:56.681 --> 32:00.886 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
overnight in mosques, are
finding informal
ways of surviving.

32:00.919 --> 32:04.489 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's very important that
they get support
as well, in addition to those
who make it

32:04.523 --> 32:06.291 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to the camps that are being set
up.

32:06.324 --> 32:09.494 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Well, in fact,
the U.N. has
already reported that, in spite
of appeals,

32:09.528 --> 32:14.332 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it had not received additional
funding for
emergency camps and all the aid
that it thinks

32:14.366 --> 32:15.600 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
it might need.

32:15.634 --> 32:17.869 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How would you describe the
shortfall at this
point?

32:17.903 --> 32:22.607 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID MILIBAND: Well, I think
that 60,000
tents have been put in place.

32:22.641 --> 32:27.546 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you think they could support
a family,
you can do the numbers yourself.

32:27.579 --> 32:31.783 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At the time of the United
Nations General
Assembly last month, the U.N.
reported that

32:31.817 --> 32:35.587 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the funding was only 30 to 40
percent of what
they -- of what was needed.

32:35.620 --> 32:40.492 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, obviously, we don't know
the kind of
exodus that's going to take
place, but everything

32:40.525 --> 32:44.896 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the president said today
suggests that the
fighting is not going to be over
quickly.

32:44.930 --> 32:50.602 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, therefore, we have to
prepare for a long
struggle in which the
humanitarian needs grow,

32:50.635 --> 32:56.074 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
both inside the city and those
outside who
have their lives disrupted for
not just weeks,

32:56.107 --> 32:57.909 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
but probably months.

32:57.943 --> 33:00.679 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Well, in fact, we
talked last
night on the program about the
military aspect

33:00.712 --> 33:02.414 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to this and how long it will
take.

33:02.447 --> 33:07.018 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I see the same reports you
do today that
longer than perhaps people even
thought.

33:07.052 --> 33:12.791 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, when you think about those
longer-term
needs from the humanitarian
aspect of this,

33:12.824 --> 33:13.792 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
what's most important?

33:13.825 --> 33:15.126 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What's crying out?

33:15.160 --> 33:17.229 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID MILIBAND: I think three
things need
to be preeminent.

33:17.262 --> 33:23.468 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
First of all, all men and boys
over the age
of 14 are going to be screened
when they leave

33:23.501 --> 33:26.404 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the city, screened for obvious
security reasons.

33:26.438 --> 33:31.209 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's imperative, given the
lessons in Fallujah
and elsewhere, that there's
independent monitoring

33:31.243 --> 33:32.978 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of those screening arrangements.

33:33.011 --> 33:37.649 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Otherwise, the fear of
persecution is going
to lead to chaos and frankly to
dangerous

33:37.682 --> 33:39.584 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
decisions being made by
individuals.

33:39.618 --> 33:44.723 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Secondly, we need to make sure
that, as the
camps fill up, those outside
camps get better

33:44.756 --> 33:46.524 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
support.

33:46.558 --> 33:49.227 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The best means of support,
frankly, is to
get them cash, because it's a
market economy

33:49.261 --> 33:53.398 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and these people will have used
up their savings
to get out of the city.

33:53.431 --> 33:56.434 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The third element is obviously
the situation
of those still trapped inside.

33:56.468 --> 34:02.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's a lot of fear of land
mines and other
need for specialists' help to
help those civilians

34:02.207 --> 34:05.944 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who are inside the city, even
before you get
to the new building process
afterwards.

34:05.977 --> 34:09.347 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And just briefly,
if you could,
to the extent that there are
many military

34:09.381 --> 34:12.517 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
forces involved in this, is it
clear who is
in charge?

34:12.550 --> 34:14.386 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Is that a concern as well?

34:14.419 --> 34:17.989 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID MILIBAND: I think it's a
very dangerous
situation for the staff of an
NGO like ours.

34:18.023 --> 34:20.225 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
These are local Iraqi people.

34:20.258 --> 34:22.727 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They're local people who are
working for us.

34:22.761 --> 34:24.496 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Of course, it's a sovereign
government.

34:24.529 --> 34:27.165 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The legitimate government of
Iraq is in charge.

34:27.198 --> 34:31.603 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But you're right to point out
the multitude
of different factions and the
danger of civilians

34:31.636 --> 34:34.039 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
being caught in the crossfire.

34:34.072 --> 34:38.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's why, at an absolute
minimum, effective
coordination across the -- those
supporting

34:38.743 --> 34:41.179 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the Iraqi government is
absolutely imperative.

34:41.212 --> 34:44.015 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: David Miliband of
the International
Rescue Committee, thank you once
again.

34:44.049 --> 34:49.888 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID MILIBAND: Thank you very
much.

34:49.921 --> 35:02.667 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Next: In a world
struggling
to accommodate a record number
of refugees,

35:02.701 --> 35:05.503 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
one country has been notably
welcoming.

35:05.537 --> 35:09.574 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Special correspondent Fred de
Sam Lazaro has
a report from Uganda.

35:09.607 --> 35:11.910 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's part of his Agents for
Change series.

35:11.943 --> 35:19.617 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Nakivale in
Southern Uganda
looks like any other dusty rural
African town.

35:19.651 --> 35:26.624 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What's remarkable is that almost
none of its
113,000 residents are Ugandan.

35:26.658 --> 35:28.226 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Ethiopia?

35:28.259 --> 35:32.964 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
All of these schoolchildren and
their parents
are refugees.

35:32.998 --> 35:34.366 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Burundi?

35:34.399 --> 35:35.800 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Rwanda?

35:35.834 --> 35:37.702 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Congo?

35:37.736 --> 35:45.477 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
All told, 13 nations are
represented in this
crowded school, their families
fleeing conflicts

35:45.510 --> 35:50.815 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
across a wide swathe of East
Africa and finding
haven in what must rank as one
of the world's

35:50.849 --> 35:53.918 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
most hospitable countries to
refugees.

35:53.952 --> 35:58.223 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In Uganda, refugees are placed
in settlements
and not camps, and the
government says there's

35:58.256 --> 36:00.091 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
an important difference.

36:00.125 --> 36:04.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Camps tend to confine people,
whereas, in
Uganda, when refugees arrive,
they are issued

36:04.529 --> 36:10.402 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
legal I.D.s that entitle them to
move freely
anywhere in the country, to find
a job, start

36:10.435 --> 36:14.472 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a business, put their children
in school.

36:14.506 --> 36:18.376 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Refugees in rural areas are
given a small
plot of land to farm.

36:18.410 --> 36:20.979 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Others migrate to the urban
areas.

36:21.012 --> 36:25.917 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Somalis are among the earlier
arrivals in
recent years.

36:25.950 --> 36:30.622 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Their enclaves in the capital,
Kampala, are
well-established with small
businesses and

36:30.655 --> 36:36.327 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
mosques, a predominantly Muslim
community
in a mostly Christian nation.

36:36.361 --> 36:40.198 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Mohammed Abdi runs this grocery
story with
his partner, Zahara Hassan.

36:40.231 --> 36:44.969 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MOHAMMED ABDI, Somali Immigrant
(through translator):
We have very many Ugandan
customers and we

36:45.003 --> 36:45.970 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
are friends.

36:46.004 --> 36:48.773 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I am one of the Somali elders in
the community.

36:48.807 --> 36:52.644 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We interact with the elders of
the Ugandan
community, whether leaders in
this distract

36:52.677 --> 36:53.645 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
or region.

36:53.678 --> 36:55.780 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we are friends, and they
welcome us.

36:55.814 --> 36:56.781 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We're very happy.

36:56.815 --> 36:58.616 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We're like one people.

36:58.650 --> 37:02.153 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: And one
scholar who's
studied refugees in Uganda says
there's reason

37:02.187 --> 37:03.988 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to be happy

37:04.022 --> 37:06.658 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ALEXANDER BETTS, Oxford
University: We showed
in the capital city of Uganda,
Kampala, 20

37:06.691 --> 37:10.628 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
percent of refugees own
businesses that employ
someone else.

37:10.662 --> 37:14.699 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And of those they employ, 40
percent are citizens
of the host country.

37:14.732 --> 37:17.802 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So refugees can contribute to
the host societies
that they're part of.

37:17.836 --> 37:23.174 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Oxford
University's Alexander
Betts says Uganda is the
exception in a world

37:23.208 --> 37:28.379 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
where refugees face widespread
hostility,
often stoked by politicians.

37:28.413 --> 37:32.484 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALEXANDER BETTS: It's all too
easy to have
a race to the bottom in terms of
political

37:32.517 --> 37:37.422 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
standards, where provincial and
municipal
politicians or national
politicians say, these

37:37.455 --> 37:38.656 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
people are a burden.

37:38.690 --> 37:40.592 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We have to keep them out.

37:40.625 --> 37:44.295 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: And while
many politicians,
especially in Western
democracies, must tread

37:44.329 --> 37:50.702 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
carefully on this issue, Betts
says it's not
a problem in Uganda, where one
man rules virtually

37:50.735 --> 37:52.504 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
unchallenged.

37:52.537 --> 37:55.907 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALEXANDER BETTS: President
Museveni has been
able to adopt refugee policies
that are a

37:55.940 --> 38:00.345 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
little different, in part
because there are
lower standards of
accountability to the public.

38:00.378 --> 38:05.150 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, not having democratic
standards is definitely
not something to celebrate, but
it highlights

38:05.183 --> 38:11.222 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the difficulties for democracies
to open up
their economies to non-citizens.

38:11.256 --> 38:13.057 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It's a hard thing for
politicians.

38:13.091 --> 38:17.929 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Recent
history might also
account for Uganda's hospitality
to refugees.

38:17.962 --> 38:22.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Yoweri Museveni
himself lived in
exile for years during and after
the bloody

38:22.834 --> 38:25.103 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
dictatorship of Idi Amin.

38:25.136 --> 38:27.472 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Museveni's rebels took power 30
years ago.

38:27.505 --> 38:29.240 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REV.

38:29.274 --> 38:32.377 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ZAC NIRINGIYE, Bishop, Anglican
Church of
Uganda: There's been a history
of violence

38:32.410 --> 38:34.045 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in this region.

38:34.078 --> 38:38.016 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Zac
Niringiye is a bishop
in the Anglican Church of
Uganda.

38:38.049 --> 38:39.517 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REV.

38:39.551 --> 38:44.756 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ZAC NIRINGIYE: South Sudan,
Rwanda, Burundi,
even Congo and even Uganda.

38:44.789 --> 38:51.462 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that that has created a
sense of being
hospitable, because you never
know.

38:51.496 --> 38:53.364 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It may be your turn next.

38:53.398 --> 38:58.803 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Despite
praise for its
hospitality, life in Uganda is
far from perfect

38:58.836 --> 39:00.672 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for refugees.

39:00.705 --> 39:05.376 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Their number has doubled in the
past five
years to more than
half-a-million, most recently

39:05.410 --> 39:10.181 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
from separate conflicts in
Burundi and South
Sudan.

39:10.215 --> 39:15.687 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Many refugees, like Abebesh
Gebreslassie,
remain haunted by the ordeal
that brought

39:15.720 --> 39:17.488 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
them here.

39:17.522 --> 39:20.158 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ABEBESH GEBRESLASSIE, Refugee
from Eritrea
(through translator): My husband
was killed,

39:20.191 --> 39:22.493 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
my son was killed, and also my
daughter.

39:22.527 --> 39:27.332 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: A son and
daughter died
in their escape from Eritrea,
part of the

39:27.365 --> 39:32.237 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
exodus of hundreds of thousands
from a country
notorious for human rights
abuses.

39:32.270 --> 39:36.608 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Her son-in-law made it to Libya,
but died
in the Mediterranean.

39:36.641 --> 39:42.880 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Gebreslassie survived the
journey of thousands
of miles on foot and on trucks
with her then

39:42.914 --> 39:45.016 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
6-year-old twin son and
daughter.

39:45.049 --> 39:49.921 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But she made a wrenching
decision to leave
two older teenaged children
behind.

39:49.954 --> 39:54.392 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ABEBESH GEBRESLASSIE (through
translator):
I feared if we all died, like my
son who was

39:54.425 --> 39:55.760 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
shot.

39:55.793 --> 39:58.696 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I left them so that our family
can survive,
can be represented.

39:58.730 --> 40:00.932 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: They are
still there now?

40:00.965 --> 40:02.967 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ABEBESH GEBRESLASSIE (through
translator):
I don't know.

40:03.001 --> 40:04.802 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I don't know.

40:04.836 --> 40:07.739 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Along the
way, she also
took custody of her orphaned
granddaughter,

40:07.772 --> 40:09.574 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Sara, who's now four.

40:09.607 --> 40:14.245 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ABEBESH GEBRESLASSIE (through
translator):
I don't care if I die here, but
I want a better

40:14.279 --> 40:17.615 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
future for my children, and
that's not possible
without a good education.

40:17.649 --> 40:23.888 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: That's not
likely in the
crowded school her children
attend, with 120

40:23.921 --> 40:29.260 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
students in each classroom, and
perhaps, because
of that, teachers who aren't
very sympathetic.

40:29.294 --> 40:32.730 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There are severe consequences
for being late,
for instance.

40:32.764 --> 40:33.765 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
They beat you?

40:33.798 --> 40:34.766 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
STUDENT: Yes.

40:34.799 --> 40:36.834 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Who beats
you?

40:36.868 --> 40:39.337 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
STUDENT: The teachers, yes, they
beat me.

40:39.370 --> 40:41.673 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The teachers, they say, if you
come late,
we wash the toilets.

40:41.706 --> 40:43.441 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: So, if
you're late, you
have wash the toilets.

40:43.474 --> 40:45.209 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
STUDENT: Yes.

40:45.243 --> 40:47.612 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: "They don't
understand,"
she said, "that I'm late because
I've gone

40:47.645 --> 40:50.548 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to fetch water and helped my
mother with the
chores."

40:50.581 --> 40:56.521 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
In the end, Ugandan and
international officials
say it boils down to resources,
or a lack

40:56.554 --> 40:58.323 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
of them.

40:58.356 --> 41:03.761 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Uganda may be hospitable, but it
has a gross
domestic product of just $600
per year per

41:03.795 --> 41:04.996 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
person.

41:05.029 --> 41:08.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Nakivale's school is funded by
the U.N.'s
Refugee Agency.

41:08.466 --> 41:14.772 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It gives Uganda some $200
million annually
in refugee aid, a fraction of
what's needed,

41:14.806 --> 41:20.511 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but not likely to increase amid
the demands
on donor governments for
refugees out of Syria,

41:20.545 --> 41:23.214 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Iraq, Ukraine and elsewhere.

41:23.247 --> 41:25.917 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Charles Yaxley is the U.N.
agency's spokesman
in Uganda.

41:25.950 --> 41:29.687 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHARLES YAXLEY, United Nations
High Commissioner
for Refugees in Uganda: Around
the world,

41:29.721 --> 41:34.125 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
humanitarian financing is
arguably at breaking
point.

41:34.158 --> 41:38.663 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Currently, humanitarian appeals
for South
Sudanese and Burundian refugees
in Uganda,

41:38.696 --> 41:40.798 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
both of those appeals are
severely underfunded.

41:40.832 --> 41:46.170 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We've received less than a
quarter of the
money we need for 2016, and that
leaves real

41:46.204 --> 41:48.806 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
gaps in our humanitarian
response.

41:48.840 --> 41:55.246 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It means we're not able to
provide the education
support for children such as
better schools,

41:55.279 --> 41:57.181 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
more schools, more teachers.

41:57.215 --> 42:02.520 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: That does
not bode well
for the future of Abebesh
Gebreslassie's twins,

42:02.553 --> 42:05.990 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
