of personal
attacks that the candidates took
on each other?

47:23.574 --> 47:24.542 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
How do you discuss it?

47:24.575 --> 47:26.377 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
CHRISTOPHER CAVANAUGH: Right.

47:26.410 --> 47:30.314 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, I think I try to couch it
in historical
terms, in the fact that, you
know, I think

47:30.347 --> 47:36.220 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
mudslinging is nothing new in
American politics,
or not new in politics, period.

47:36.253 --> 47:38.656 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You can go back to the Roman
states with Cicero.

47:38.689 --> 47:44.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Or one of my favorites is to
discuss the election
of 1800, where Jefferson accused
Adams of

47:44.729 --> 47:51.969 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
having hermaphroditical
tendencies, and Adams
said that Jefferson had a
mulatto father.

47:52.002 --> 47:55.673 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, slinging mud is nothing new
in American
politics.

47:55.706 --> 48:01.212 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's tough to get the kids to
sort through
that to get to those policies
and to be able

48:01.245 --> 48:07.485 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to lay those policies side by
side to get
to see what the candidates are
proposing.

48:07.518 --> 48:12.323 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Richard House,
as you assigned
your students to keep track of
policy positions,

48:12.356 --> 48:14.959 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
did they notice what was being
talked about
and what wasn't?

48:14.992 --> 48:19.363 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICHARD HOUSE: I think there was
definitely
a notice of the issues that they
were focusing

48:19.396 --> 48:23.234 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on, but, at the same time,
they're always
-- they're middle schoolers.

48:23.267 --> 48:25.035 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There's a certain maturity level
there.

48:25.069 --> 48:29.340 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They notice what these
candidates are saying
and the hateful rhetoric that is
coming out

48:29.373 --> 48:30.708 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of their mouths.

48:30.741 --> 48:33.544 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, you have to forewarn them:
We're not going
to focus on that.

48:33.577 --> 48:35.279 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We're going to take the high
road.

48:35.312 --> 48:38.549 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And some of the things that are
coming out
of these candidates' mouths, I
don't want

48:38.582 --> 48:40.317 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
them coming out of yours.

48:40.351 --> 48:43.621 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I do want them to be able to
formulate their
own opinions, but, at the same
time, they

48:43.654 --> 48:47.391 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
also have to know that, in my
classroom, bigotry
and hate doesn't have a place.

48:47.424 --> 48:51.729 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Richard, what
about the
administration or parents
knowing that these

48:51.762 --> 48:55.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
conversations are happening in
the classrooms
of their children?

48:55.199 --> 48:56.167 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Have they been supportive?

48:56.200 --> 48:57.968 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
RICHARD HOUSE: I think so.

48:58.002 --> 49:03.140 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think my goal this year is to
bring certain
as we -- current events to
issue, to light

49:03.174 --> 49:04.375 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in my classroom.

49:04.408 --> 49:05.910 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We focused on police brutality.

49:05.943 --> 49:10.147 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We talked about Colin
Kaepernick's protest.

49:10.181 --> 49:14.852 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And after that, I got an e-mail
from a parent
thanking me for bringing those
issues to light,

49:14.885 --> 49:20.357 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that they were able to have a
substantive
conversation about police
brutality and privilege,

49:20.391 --> 49:22.593 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
something that they normally
might not have
had at the dinner table.

49:22.626 --> 49:28.032 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, I think parents are
appreciative when
teachers do bring to light
certain issues

49:28.065 --> 49:29.834 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that are currently going on in
our country.

49:29.867 --> 49:33.070 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Chris
Cavanaugh, how do
you walk the line between
teaching them how

49:33.103 --> 49:34.805 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to think and not what to think?

49:34.839 --> 49:40.077 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRISTOPHER CAVANAUGH: Well, I
think it's
important to create -- listening
to Richard

49:40.110 --> 49:44.215 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
speak, I think it's important to
create that
environment where it's a safe
environment,

49:44.248 --> 49:47.718 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
especially maybe for my
students, being a
little bit older and maybe a
little further

49:47.751 --> 49:54.058 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
along in the political
socialization process,
to have them start to -- a safe
environment

49:54.091 --> 49:58.195 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to express those ideas and then
to get them
to examine themselves.

49:58.229 --> 50:03.734 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I like to play devil's advocate
quite a bit
with my students, regardless of
what they

50:03.767 --> 50:10.007 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
support, and to challenge them
on those views
to get them to reexamine their
own views.

50:10.040 --> 50:16.347 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, thankfully, you know, we're
well aware
of fact-checking organizations
that exist,

50:16.380 --> 50:21.652 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
so we can go back and fact-check
debates to
see what the candidates have
said and how

50:21.685 --> 50:24.521 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
well it holds up under scrutiny.

50:24.555 --> 50:27.491 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Richard, how
do the facts
play into it?

50:27.524 --> 50:29.226 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Technically, they're coming into
your classroom.

50:29.260 --> 50:34.932 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're expecting you to maybe
help them see
what is true and what isn't.

50:34.965 --> 50:36.734 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
How do you get that across?

50:36.767 --> 50:40.504 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICHARD HOUSE: I think, a lot of
times, it's
my job to guide their thinking,
but not tell

50:40.537 --> 50:44.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
them what to think, give them
the resources
out there, so that they can go
out and do

50:44.742 --> 50:47.878 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the research and formulate an
opinion on their
own.

50:47.912 --> 50:50.347 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For example, today, we were
talking about
voting.

50:50.381 --> 50:53.550 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We registered to vote for a mock
election
that we're going to have in with
weeks.

50:53.584 --> 50:55.419 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And then we focused on voter
I.D. laws.

50:55.452 --> 51:00.491 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I presented information on,
these are how
voter I.D. laws impact people
across this

51:00.524 --> 51:02.293 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
country.

51:02.326 --> 51:05.863 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Do you think that -- and I posed
the question,
do you think this is done
because of voter

51:05.896 --> 51:11.035 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
fraud, or is it done because --
to place an
unnecessary burden on minority
voters?

51:11.068 --> 51:13.304 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then I wanted them to be
able to formulate
their own opinion.

51:13.337 --> 51:17.241 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, it's my job to present them
with the information
they need, but it's their job to
form their

51:17.274 --> 51:19.043 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
own opinion.

51:19.076 --> 51:21.712 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Finally,
Chris, in this
day and age, your students can
be fairly active

51:21.745 --> 51:23.580 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
during the debate.

51:23.614 --> 51:26.784 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The next morning, when you look
past through
their Twitter feeds or their
Facebook comments,

51:26.817 --> 51:28.352 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
what are you looking for?

51:28.385 --> 51:30.454 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRISTOPHER CAVANAUGH: Honestly,
I try not
to do that.

51:30.487 --> 51:32.256 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

51:32.289 --> 51:36.193 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRISTOPHER CAVANAUGH: I have
only had a couple
kids where I have had to go back
and say,

51:36.226 --> 51:41.532 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
